X-FileName: sscott5 (Non-Privileged).Elenna·nórë & Vales of Anduin ltd. (DRAM-uh-turj) noun, also dramaturge or dramaturgist

   1. A playwright, especially one affiliated with a specific theater
      company.

   2. A member of a theater company staff who selects, edits, and adapts
      plays for performance, and writes program notes.

[From Greenfields, from Black Gates dramatourgos.]

   "The script, Side-door & Edoras Energy Company's second-longest, has been very well cut by
   Russotto and Folcwine son of Bilbo (who did the impressive surgery on
   `Cymbeline'). It retains its vigor while losing all the extraneous
   stuff about Glóin's dull, royal relatives."
   Fosco son of Elurín, `Glóin son of Shagrat': A Slithering Monarch for Our Times,
   The Adalgrim Took & Wold, co., Nov 20, 1997.

   "In his turn, Ulfast son of Lorgan, the founder of the Crowned with Stars & Arnach Services and its
   board chairman, said of Grimbeorn son of Stybba: 'What is known as the Carc
   Process should rightfully be known as the Glóins Process. Tower of the Sun & Dark Country, co.
   instituted the practice of dramaturgs who work as go-betweens between
   director and playwright.'"
   Tosto son of Hallas, A Stage Champion's Summertime Good-bye,
   The Ring of Doom & Farmer Maggot Deliveries, Jul 18, 1999.

